ce:section.ce:para:
The optical properties of CQDs were examined by UV-Vis and fluorescence spectroscopy. Two absorption maxima at 295 and 350 nm (Fig. 3
                        A) correspond to the π→π* transition of the inner core of the CQDs and n→π* transition of the C=O bond, respectively [49]. The excitation maximum of CQDs is at 350 nm, while emission maximum is at 450 nm. Upon illumination of daylight lamp and UV-visible light lamp, the CQDs aqueous solution shows light yellow and bright blue color, respectively (Inset of Fig. 3A). Comparing with quinine sulfate as a quantum yield reference, the calculated quantum yield of CQDs (ΦS
                        ) at 350 nm was 0.17 (Fig. S3). The fluorescence emission spectra of CQDs at different excitation wavelengths (λex) are given in Fig. 3B. With the increase of λex from 310 to 500 nm, the emission maxima of CQDs red shifts from 443 to 557 nm. It indicates that CQDs have λex-dependent fluorescence property, which is typically observed in carbon-based quantum dots [50]. This λex-dependent fluorescence property is believed to arise from the surface states formed by various functional groups of CQDs and different size distribution of CQDs which affect band gad of CQDs [51,52]. At certain excitation wavelength, some corresponding emissive sites are excited and result in the λex-dependent behavior in emission spectra.
